## What Is DNS? (The Simple Version)

Before running any command, I want to explain what DNS is, because
without understanding it, the results are just numbers.

When someone types google.com into a browser, the computer does not
actually know where google.com lives. Computers only understand numbers
— things like 172.217.194.138. DNS is the system that translates the
name into the number.

Think of it like a phone book. A person's name is google.com. Their
phone number is 172.217.194.138. DNS is what connects one to the other.

Every single time a device loads a website or sends an email, a DNS
lookup happens first — quietly, in the background, before anything
else. Most people never see it. But it is always there.

