## What I Did — Step by Step

### Step 1 — I used nslookup to ask about five websites

nslookup is the simplest of the three tools. I type a domain name,
and it asks my DNS server to translate that name into an IP address
and shows me the answer.

I ran it on both machines — Kali and Linux Mint — for all five domains.

Here is what came back on Kali first:

Server:  10.218.101.182
Address: 10.218.101.182#53

Kali sent its question to 10.218.101.182 — my mobile hotspot gateway.
The #53 at the end means port 53, which is the port DNS always uses.
Every DNS server in the world listens on port 53. I already know this
from the earlier labs where port 53 appeared in scans.

Then I ran the same commands on Linux Mint and got something different
in the server line:

Server:  127.0.0.53
Address: 127.0.0.53#53

Linux Mint showed 127.0.0.53 instead of the gateway. This confused me
at first. 127.0.0.53 is not an external server — it is the machine
talking to itself. Linux Mint has a built-in DNS helper called
systemd-resolved that sits between the application and the real DNS
server. When Mint needs a DNS answer, it asks this local helper first.
The helper then goes to the gateway, gets the answer, and brings it
back. Same result, one extra step in the middle.

The results from both machines for all five domains:

facebook.com  → 157.240.15.35
github.com    → 20.205.243.166
bbc.com       → 151.101.128.81 (plus three more addresses)
linkedin.com  → 150.171.22.12
google.com    → 172.217.194.138 (plus five more addresses)

Both machines returned exactly the same addresses for every domain.
That matching result matters — I will come back to why when I get to
the dig section.

### A mistake I made on Linux Mint

When I went to type nslookup for linkedin.com on Linux Mint, I
accidentally typed this:

shohail@shohail-X542UA:~$ nslooiup linkedin.com
Command 'nslooiup' not found

The terminal immediately told me the command did not exist and suggested
the correct spelling. I typed it correctly the next time and it worked.

This happens. The terminal does not guess what someone means — it reads
exactly what is typed, letter by letter. A single wrong character and
the command does not run. The right response is to read the error,
fix the typo, and try again. Nothing breaks. Nothing is lost.
---

Every nslookup result on both machines carried this line above the answer:

    Non-authoritative answer:

This line appears because my router did not find the answer itself. It
went and asked someone else — my ISP's DNS server further up the chain —
and then passed that answer back to me. The router is relaying information
it received from elsewhere, not answering from its own knowledge. That
is what non-authoritative means. An authoritative answer would only come
from the DNS server that actually owns and manages that domain — Google's
own name servers for google.com, for example. Everything else in between
is just passing the answer along.

Several domains also returned two types of addresses instead of one.
Facebook, BBC, LinkedIn, and Google all came back with both an address
starting with numbers like 157.240.15.35 and a longer address starting
with something like 2a03:2880 or 2404:6800. The shorter one is an IPv4
address — the older, more common format that most of the internet still
runs on. The longer one is an IPv6 address — a newer format introduced
because the world was running out of IPv4 addresses. There are only
about four billion possible IPv4 addresses, and they are nearly all
taken. IPv6 has so many possible addresses that running out is not a
practical concern. Domains that return both types support both formats
and will connect using whichever one the requesting device prefers.
GitHub returned only an IPv4 address, which means it either does not
yet support IPv6 or was not advertising it at the time of the query.

