### Step 2 — I used dig to get more detail

dig does the same job as nslookup but shows much more of what is
happening underneath. Instead of just the answer, it shows the full
structure of the DNS response — how long it took, how long the answer
is valid, which server responded, and how big the response was.

I ran dig google.com on both machines.

**Kali:**

google.com.   152   IN   A   172.217.194.138
google.com.   152   IN   A   172.217.194.139
google.com.   152   IN   A   172.217.194.101
google.com.   152   IN   A   172.217.194.113
google.com.   152   IN   A   172.217.194.102
google.com.   152   IN   A   172.217.194.100
Query time: 4 msec
Server: 10.218.101.182#53

**Linux Mint:**

google.com.   91    IN   A   172.217.194.100
google.com.   91    IN   A   172.217.194.138
google.com.   91    IN   A   172.217.194.139
google.com.   91    IN   A   172.217.194.101
google.com.   91    IN   A   172.217.194.113
google.com.   91    IN   A   172.217.194.102
Query time: 4 msec
Server: 127.0.0.53#53

Same six IP addresses on both machines. The number before IN A is the
TTL — Time To Live. It counts down in seconds and tells the machine
how long to remember this answer before asking again. Kali showed 152
and Mint showed 91 because the two machines asked at slightly different
moments. The countdown had already ticked further on one than the other.
Not a problem — just timing.

**dig google.com +short**

This strips everything away and prints only the addresses. Useful when
the full output is not needed.

Kali
172.217.194.100
172.217.194.113
172.217.194.139
Linux Mint
172.217.194.102
172.217.194.101
172.217.194.138

Same addresses, different order. Google has many servers around the
world and rotates which ones it lists first each time someone asks.
This spreads the traffic so no single server gets too busy. It is
called load balancing.

**dig google.com MX**

MX records show which mail servers handle email for a domain.

google.com.   180   IN   MX   10 smtp.google.com.

Both machines returned the same result. Email for google.com goes
through smtp.google.com. The number 10 is a priority — if there were
multiple mail servers listed, the one with the lowest number would
be tried first.

**dig google.com @8.8.8.8 — asking Google's own DNS directly**

This command skips my local DNS server completely and sends the question
directly to 8.8.8.8, which is Google's public DNS server. It is a way
to bypass the router and go straight to a known, trusted source.

Kali via 8.8.8.8
google.com.   205   IN   A   172.217.194.139
(same six addresses)
Query time: 84 msec

Linux Mint via 8.8.8.8
google.com.   158   IN   A   172.217.194.113
(same six addresses)
Query time: 72 msec

Both queries through 8.8.8.8 took around 80 milliseconds. The same
query through the local gateway took only 4 milliseconds. The gateway
is physically close — just a few meters away in the same room. Google's
DNS server at 8.8.8.8 is somewhere across the world. Distance adds time.

The more important thing here is that the addresses matched. Both the
local gateway and Google's public DNS returned the exact same IP
addresses for google.com. If they had returned different addresses,
that would mean something was interfering with DNS — redirecting traffic
to a fake address instead of the real one. That attack has a name: DNS
hijacking. The matching results here confirmed it was not happening.

