### Step 3 — I used whois to find out who owns google.com

whois queries a registration database and returns information about
who registered a domain, when they registered it, when it expires,
and which name servers it uses. This information is public — anyone
can ask.

I ran whois google.com on both machines and got the same output.

Registrant Organization: Google LLC
Registrant Country: US
Creation Date: 1997-09-15
Expiry Date:   2028-09-14
Registrar: MarkMonitor Inc.
Name Servers: ns1.google.com through ns4.google.com
DNSSEC: unsigned

A few things from this are worth understanding.

google.com was registered in 1997 — nearly thirty years ago. This
matters in security work because attackers often register new domains
that look like real ones — something like g00gle.com or googIe.com
with a capital I instead of a lowercase L. A domain registered last
week claiming to be a major company is suspicious. A domain registered
in 1997 is not.

MarkMonitor is a registrar that specialises in protecting well-known
brand names. Large companies use them specifically because they add
extra layers of protection against domain theft.

The domain status lines — clientDeleteProhibited,
serverTransferProhibited, and others — are locks. They prevent the
domain from being deleted, transferred, or modified without going
through extra verification steps. High-value domains like google.com
carry all of these locks.

DNSSEC unsigned is interesting. DNSSEC is a security extension that
adds a digital signature to DNS responses, making it harder to tamper
with them. Even Google's own domain does not use it on the .com record.
This is a reminder that even large, well-resourced organisations do not
always implement every available security measure.

