## What I Learned

DNS is running silently behind everything that happens on the internet.
Every website visit, every email, every app that connects to a server —
all of it starts with a DNS lookup that most people never see.

The tools in this lab — nslookup, dig, whois — are not complex. But
what they reveal is. In a real investigation, these same tools pointed
at an unfamiliar domain can reveal whether a website is impersonating
a real one, whether email is being redirected, whether a domain was
registered recently and suspiciously, and whether the DNS server itself
is giving honest answers.

None of those problems appeared here because well-known public domains
were used. The value of running these commands on safe, known targets
first is that the results look like what normal, correct output should
look like. When something abnormal appears in the future, it will stand
out because normal is now familiar.

